  monumentInformation:
    monumentInformation:
    - title: Who Built It
      details:
      - The Great Stupa at Sanchi was originally commissioned by Emperor Ashoka of
        the Maurya Dynasty in the 3rd century BCE to preserve and spread the relics
        of the Buddha.
      - The structure was later expanded and decorated by subsequent rulers of the
        Shunga Dynasty, who added elaborate gateways and railings.
    - title: Where It Is Located
      details:
      - The Sanchi Stupa is located in the town of Sanchi, in the state of Madhya
        Pradesh, India, atop a hill that offers a panoramic view of the surrounding
        area.
      - It is situated about 46 kilometers from Bhopal, the capital of Madhya Pradesh,
        making it a prominent Buddhist pilgrimage and historical site in central
        India.
    - title: When It Was Built
      details:
      - The construction of the original Stupa at Sanchi began in the 3rd century
        BCE, under the reign of Emperor Ashoka, as part of his efforts to promote
        Buddhism.
      - The stupa underwent significant expansions and renovations during the Shunga
        period, around the 2nd century BCE, adding ornate carvings and architectural
        enhancements.
    - title: How Is It Protected By
      details:
      - The Sanchi Stupa is a UNESCO World Heritage Site, recognized for its historical
        and cultural significance as one of the best-preserved ancient Buddhist monuments.
      - It is protected and maintained by the Archaeological Survey of India (ASI),
        which ensures its preservation and the upkeep of its surrounding monuments.
    - title: Why It Was Built
      details:
      - The Sanchi Stupa was built to house the relics of the Buddha, symbolizing
        the core tenets of Buddhism and serving as a place of meditation and worship.
      - Emperor Ashoka commissioned the stupa to promote Buddhism across his empire,
        making it a symbol of his conversion to the religion and his dedication to
        its spread.
